<PREVIOUS_PR_TITLE>
Initialize Spring Boot user-management backend core
</PREVIOUS_PR_TITLE>

<PREVIOUS_PR_DESCRIPTION>
### Motivation
- Provide a minimal Spring Boot backend scaffold to support a user-management module with persistence and validation.
- Use Gradle and an in-memory H2 datasource for development and tests so the module can be exercised without external infra.
- Persist session prompts to `user-prompt.log` for reproducibility and auditing of instructions.

### Description
- Add Gradle build files (`build.gradle`, `settings.gradle`) and Java 17 toolchain configuration with dependencies for JPA, validation, H2, and testing.
- Add application bootstrap `UserManagementApplication` and configuration `src/main/resources/application.yml` configured to use an in-memory H2 database.
- Implement JPA `User` entity with validation annotations, unique email constraint, and `createdAt`/`updatedAt` lifecycle timestamps.
- Add `UserRepository` with email lookup helpers, `UserService` interface, and `UserServiceImpl` with transactional CRUD operations and duplicate-email / not-found checks.
- Add a baseline Spring Boot context-load test `UserManagementApplicationTests` and a root `user-prompt.log` file containing the recorded prompts.

### Testing
- Attempted `gradle wrapper` which failed in this environment with an error `Unsupported class file major version 69` due to Gradle/JDK compatibility constraints, so wrapper generation did not complete.
- Attempted `export JAVA_HOME=... && gradle test` with a Java 17 toolchain, but plugin/dependency resolution failed due to restricted external repository access, so tests could not be executed here.
- A JUnit 5 context-load test `UserManagementApplicationTests` was added to the project and is ready to run once Gradle/plugin resolution is available; no automated tests succeeded in this environment.
</PREVIOUS_PR_DESCRIPTION>

